I think a lot about how the Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to critically view them.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to think about where they came from, because back then you couldn't easily determine that anyway.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we placed them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong inclination towards nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I ordered pizza every Thursday and watched the show together.
That was completely different from today's streaming, where 12 episodes come out all at once and everyone watches whenever they feel like it, and posts on social media with "spoiler warnings" or discusses them in closed groups.
Subconsciously, we long for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch shows like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," which contain so many one-liners that would be memes today.
We all brought these phrases and assumed that most of them already understood them.
Today, one can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads massively through virality.
There is far too much, and there is no way to systematize it. Will we ever get out of this oversaturation?
We are trapped in a vicious circle, constantly discovering new content, only to then realize that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
Therefore, we must hold on to our nostalgia while simultaneously accepting that the people who created the works we liked can also have made big mistakes.
We enter parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We know that it's difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on some people's toes along the way.
Since we have lost our collective awareness regarding the media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who elevate someone to a pedestal, only to be shocked when he falls down.
We are in a phase of upheaval and I am curious to see where it will ultimately lead.
